docs.abstract: Every year for a month, we celebrate the heroes of Black history. But these stories can obscure how change happens and who gets left behind.
docs.snippet: Every year for a month, we celebrate the heroes of Black history. But these stories can obscure how change happens and who gets left behind.
docs.lead_paragraph: This is the first piece in “Black History, Continued,” a series that will explore pivotal moments and transformative figures in Black culture and examine how the past shapes the present and the future.

headline.main: Do We Ask Too Much of Black Heroes?
headline.print_headline: How We Celebrate Heroes Obscures How Change Happens

docs.abstract: Mena Mark Hanna, who has studied colonialism in classical music, will be the first person of color to lead the renowned arts group in Charleston, S.C.
docs.snippet: Mena Mark Hanna, who has studied colonialism in classical music, will be the first person of color to lead the renowned arts group in Charleston, S.C.
docs.lead_paragraph: A scholar who has spoken forcefully about the legacy of colonialism in classical music will serve as the next general director of Spoleto Festival USA, the renowned arts group in Charleston, S.C., announced on Tuesday.

headline.main: Outspoken Music Scholar to Lead Spoleto Festival
headline.print_headline: Outspoken Scholar To Lead Spoleto Festival

docs.abstract: Voters delivered a convincing victory for Joe Biden, but a split decision for the two parties. Now Democrats and Republicans face perhaps the most up-for-grabs electoral landscape in a generation.
docs.snippet: Voters delivered a convincing victory for Joe Biden, but a split decision for the two parties. Now Democrats and Republicans face perhaps the most up-for-grabs electoral landscape in a generation.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — America’s two major parties had hoped the 2020 presidential election would render a decisive judgment on the country’s political trajectory. But after a race that broke records for voter turnout and campaign spending, neither Democrats nor Republicans have achieved a dominant upper hand.

headline.main: With Trench Warfare Deepening, Parties Face Unsettled Electoral Map
headline.print_headline: Parties Hunt for Message After Split-Decision Election

byline.original: By Jonathan Martin and Alexander Burns

docs.abstract: As corporate houses get bigger and more commercial, these publishers are doing work that is vital in the marketplace of ideas.
docs.snippet: As corporate houses get bigger and more commercial, these publishers are doing work that is vital in the marketplace of ideas.
docs.lead_paragraph: Last fall, I went around the house pulling out beloved books published by university presses because I was planning to write an essay about University Press Week, which falls during November every year. My stack of books grew high and calved into two stacks, and then again into three, all heaped in front of the bookcase next to my worktable. I had to nudge them aside every time I reached for another book. It got to where I hardly noticed them, even though they were in plain view all day long.

headline.main: University Presses Are Keeping American Literature Alive

docs.abstract: Killings of Arabs by Arabs have soared in Israel. The prevailing assumption, an official said, was “as long as they are killing each other, that’s their problem.”
docs.snippet: Killings of Arabs by Arabs have soared in Israel. The prevailing assumption, an official said, was “as long as they are killing each other, that’s their problem.”
docs.lead_paragraph: TAIBEH, Israel — After a day of work in construction, Alaa Sarsour, 25, showered, dressed and walked the short distance to his friend’s pre-wedding henna party in a cobbled alley festooned with ribbons in the old heart of Taibeh, an Arab town in central Israel.

headline.main: Violent Crime Spikes Among Arabs in Israel as Officials Admit Neglect
headline.print_headline: Killings Among Arabs Soar in Israel, Baring Its Neglect of Crime

docs.abstract: The museum will also hold public programs to examine Avery Brundage’s legacy, as well as questions around restitution, and work on “decolonizing’’ the museum.
docs.snippet: The museum will also hold public programs to examine Avery Brundage’s legacy, as well as questions around restitution, and work on “decolonizing’’ the museum.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — For 48 years, visitors to this city’s Asian Art Museum have had to pass the bust of Avery Brundage, its towering patron, an industrialist and former president of the International Olympic Committee. The museum, a jeweled attraction at Civic Center Plaza, was established in 1966 to house his nearly 8,000 art pieces.

headline.main: Asian Art Museum to Remove Bust of Patron. That’s Just a Start.

docs.abstract: A big idea in Minneapolis  points the way for other cities desperately in need of housing.
docs.snippet: A big idea in Minneapolis  points the way for other cities desperately in need of housing.
docs.lead_paragraph: Housing is one area of American life where government really is the problem. The United States is suffering from an acute shortage of affordable places to live, particularly in the urban areas where economic opportunity increasingly is concentrated. And perhaps the most important reason is that local governments are preventing construction.
